# Verification Plan: __PROJECT_NAME__

> Updated on: __DATE__
>
> Define how correctness will be proven before large-scale implementation starts.

## 1. Test Goals

- Prevent key page flows from becoming incomplete, losing state, or hiding error feedback
- Prioritize critical browser journeys for first-time and returning users

## 2. Test Layers

| Layer | Goal | Coverage | Tool / Method |
|---|---|---|---|
| White-box Unit | Verify page-local logic | validation, derived state, display conditions, key branches | [TBD, for example component tests or pure logic tests] |
| Integration | Verify page and data-layer collaboration | form submission, async requests, error feedback | [TBD, for example page integration tests] |
| E2E | Verify key user flows | first core browser flow and failure recovery | [TBD, for example browser automation tests] |
| Performance | Verify performance targets | first-interaction time, key action latency, long-list or large-data scenarios | [TBD, for example Web Vitals or benchmarks] |
| Security | Verify security boundaries | auth, authorization, input validation, sensitive output | [TBD, for example negative security tests] |

## 3. Requirement-to-Test Mapping

| Test ID | Requirement | Test Type | Core Assertion |
|---|---|---|---|
| `TEST-001` | `FR-001` | E2E | Users can complete the first core flow on the key page |
| `TEST-002` | `FR-002` | Integration | On request or validation failure, the page shows recoverable feedback |

Requirements:

- Every high-priority `FR-*` maps to at least one automated test
- White-box, performance, and security tests relevant to the current version must be included in the plan
- If a requirement cannot yet be verified automatically, document why and what the fallback verification is

## 4. First Red Tests

1. A first-time user cannot find the first action entry on the key page
2. After submitting the key form, the page does not show loading state or final result
3. When a request fails, the error feedback is missing or does not preserve context

## 5. Test Data and Fixtures

- Prepare success, failure, and empty-state page data samples
- Prepare stable accounts, seed data, or API mocks for the key browser flow

## 5.1 White-Box Focus

- Component-internal state branches
- Form-validation logic
- Error-feedback and state-transition logic

## 5.2 Performance Test Plan

- Key performance indicators: first interactive time and key action latency
- Load scenarios: large lists, repeated interactions, slow networks
- Pass criteria: [for example key-page p95 stays within target]

## 5.3 Security Test Plan

- Authentication and authorization boundaries
- Input validation and injection risk
- Whether sensitive information is exposed in UI or logs

## 6. Regression Strategy

- Key page interaction flows must keep browser regression coverage
- Any bug fix involving state management, form validation, or error feedback must add regression coverage
- Changes that affect routing, permissions, or API interaction require a full regression pass of the key path

## 7. Execution Guidance

- Start with the failing test for the first key page flow
- Prioritize interaction-heavy paths, frequent state transitions, and high-rework areas
- If the test framework is not selected yet, write the test idea and assertions first, then choose tools later
- Do not implement first and add tests later; tests should define the page-behavior boundary up front

## 8. Definition of Completion

- Every high-priority requirement has at least one automated verification path
- Critical failure scenarios are covered
- Bug fixes include regression tests
- Test commands can be run repeatedly with stable results
- White-box, performance, and security requirements are either satisfied or explicitly deferred with justification
